9 82   GLOUCESTER. Now is the winter of our discontent
9 83     Made glorious summer by this sun of York;
9 84     And all the clouds that lour'd upon our house
9 85     In the deep bosom of the ocean buried.
9 86     Now are our brows bound with victorious wreaths;
9 87     Our bruised arms hung up for monuments;
9 88     Our stern alarums chang'd to merry meetings,
9 89     Our dreadful marches to delightful measures.
9 90     Grim-visag'd war hath smooth'd his wrinkled front,
9 91     And now, instead of mounting barbed steeds
9 92     To fright the souls of fearful adversaries,
9 93     He capers nimbly in a lady's chamber
9 94     To the lascivious pleasing of a lute.
9 95     But I-that am not shap'd for sportive tricks,
9 96     Nor made to court an amorous looking-glass-
9 97     I-that am rudely stamp'd, and want love's majesty
9 98     To strut before a wanton ambling nymph-
9 99     I-that am curtail'd of this fair proportion,
9 100     Cheated of feature by dissembling nature,
9 101     Deform'd, unfinish'd, sent before my time
9 102     Into this breathing world scarce half made up,
9 103     And that so lamely and unfashionable
9 104     That dogs bark at me as I halt by them-
9 105     Why, I, in this weak piping time of peace,
9 106     Have no delight to pass away the time,
9 107     Unless to spy my shadow in the sun
9 108     And descant on mine own deformity.
9 109     And therefore, since I cannot prove a lover
9 110     To entertain these fair well-spoken days,
9 111     I am determined to prove a villain
9 112     And hate the idle pleasures of these days.
9 113     Plots have I laid, inductions dangerous,
9 114     By drunken prophecies, libels, and dreams,
9 115     To set my brother Clarence and the King
9 116     In deadly hate the one against the other;
9 117     And if King Edward be as true and just
9 118     As I am subtle, false, and treacherous,
9 119     This day should Clarence closely be mew'd up-
9 120     About a prophecy which says that G
9 121     Of Edward's heirs the murderer shall be.
9 122     Dive, thoughts, down to my soul. Here Clarence comes.
