9 126     Brother, good day. What means this armed guard
9 127     That waits upon your Grace?
9 128   CLARENCE. His Majesty,
9 129     Tend'ring my person's safety, hath appointed
9 130     This conduct to convey me to th' Tower.
9 131   GLOUCESTER. Upon what cause?
9 132   CLARENCE. Because my name is George.
9 133   GLOUCESTER. Alack, my lord, that fault is none of yours:
9 134     He should, for that, commit your godfathers.
9 135     O, belike his Majesty hath some intent
9 136     That you should be new-christ'ned in the Tower.
9 137     But what's the matter, Clarence? May I know?
9 138   CLARENCE. Yea, Richard, when I know; for I protest
9 139     As yet I do not; but, as I can learn,
9 140     He hearkens after prophecies and dreams,
9 141     And from the cross-row plucks the letter G,
9 142     And says a wizard told him that by G
9 143     His issue disinherited should be;
9 144     And, for my name of George begins with G,
9 145     It follows in his thought that I am he.
9 146     These, as I learn, and such like toys as these
9 147     Hath mov'd his Highness to commit me now.
9 148   GLOUCESTER. Why, this it is when men are rul'd by women:
9 149     'Tis not the King that sends you to the Tower;
9 150     My Lady Grey his wife, Clarence, 'tis she
9 151     That tempers him to this extremity.
9 152     Was it not she and that good man of worship,
9 153     Antony Woodville, her brother there,
9 154     That made him send Lord Hastings to the Tower,
9 155     From whence this present day he is delivered?
9 156     We are not safe, Clarence; we are not safe.
9 157   CLARENCE. By heaven, I think there is no man is secure
9 158     But the Queen's kindred, and night-walking heralds
9 159     That trudge betwixt the King and Mistress Shore.
9 160     Heard you not what an humble suppliant
9 161     Lord Hastings was, for her delivery?
9 162   GLOUCESTER. Humbly complaining to her deity
9 163     Got my Lord Chamberlain his liberty.
9 164     I'll tell you what-I think it is our way,
9 165     If we will keep in favour with the King,
9 166     To be her men and wear her livery:
9 167     The jealous o'er-worn widow, and herself,
9 168     Since that our brother dubb'd them gentlewomen,
9 169     Are mighty gossips in our monarchy.
9 170   BRAKENBURY. I beseech your Graces both to pardon me:
9 171     His Majesty hath straitly given in charge
9 172     That no man shall have private conference,
9 173     Of what degree soever, with your brother.
9 174   GLOUCESTER. Even so; an't please your worship, Brakenbury,
9 175     You may partake of any thing we say:
9 176     We speak no treason, man; we say the King
9 177     Is wise and virtuous, and his noble queen
9 178     Well struck in years, fair, and not jealous;
9 179     We say that Shore's wife hath a pretty foot,
9 180     A cherry lip, a bonny eye, a passing pleasing tongue;
9 181     And that the Queen's kindred are made gentlefolks.
9 182     How say you, sir? Can you deny all this?
9 183   BRAKENBURY. With this, my lord, myself have naught to do.
9 184   GLOUCESTER. Naught to do with Mistress Shore! I tell thee,
9 185     fellow,
9 186     He that doth naught with her, excepting one,
9 187     Were best to do it secretly alone.
9 188   BRAKENBURY. What one, my lord?
9 189   GLOUCESTER. Her husband, knave! Wouldst thou betray me?
9 190   BRAKENBURY. I do beseech your Grace to pardon me, and
9 191     withal
9 192     Forbear your conference with the noble Duke.
9 193   CLARENCE. We know thy charge, Brakenbury, and will
9 194     obey.
9 195   GLOUCESTER. We are the Queen's abjects and must obey.
9 196     Brother, farewell; I will unto the King;
9 197     And whatsoe'er you will employ me in-
9 198     Were it to call King Edward's widow sister-
9 199     I will perform it to enfranchise you.
