9 240     He cannot live, I hope, and must not die
9 241     Till George be pack'd with posthorse up to heaven.
9 242     I'll in to urge his hatred more to Clarence
9 243     With lies well steel'd with weighty arguments;
9 244     And, if I fail not in my deep intent,
9 245     Clarence hath not another day to live;
9 246     Which done, God take King Edward to his mercy,
9 247     And leave the world for me to bustle in!
9 248     For then I'll marry Warwick's youngest daughter.
9 249     What though I kill'd her husband and her father?
9 250     The readiest way to make the wench amends
9 251     Is to become her husband and her father;
9 252     The which will I-not all so much for love
9 253     As for another secret close intent
