9 269   ANNE. Set down, set down your honourable load-
9 270     If honour may be shrouded in a hearse;
9 271     Whilst I awhile obsequiously lament
9 272     Th' untimely fall of virtuous Lancaster.
9 273     Poor key-cold figure of a holy king!
9 274     Pale ashes of the house of Lancaster!
9 275     Thou bloodless remnant of that royal blood!
9 276     Be it lawful that I invocate thy ghost
9 277     To hear the lamentations of poor Anne,
9 278     Wife to thy Edward, to thy slaughtered son,
9 279     Stabb'd by the self-same hand that made these wounds.
9 280     Lo, in these windows that let forth thy life
9 281     I pour the helpless balm of my poor eyes.
9 282     O, cursed be the hand that made these holes!
9 283     Cursed the heart that had the heart to do it!
9 284     Cursed the blood that let this blood from hence!
9 285     More direful hap betide that hated wretch
9 286     That makes us wretched by the death of thee
9 287     Than I can wish to adders, spiders, toads,
9 288     Or any creeping venom'd thing that lives!
9 289     If ever he have child, abortive be it,
9 290     Prodigious, and untimely brought to light,
9 291     Whose ugly and unnatural aspect
9 292     May fright the hopeful mother at the view,
9 293     And that be heir to his unhappiness!
9 294     If ever he have wife, let her be made
9 295     More miserable by the death of him
9 296     Than I am made by my young lord and thee!
9 297     Come, now towards Chertsey with your holy load,
9 298     Taken from Paul's to be interred there;
9 299     And still as you are weary of this weight
9 300     Rest you, whiles I lament King Henry's corse.
