9 525     To take her in her heart's extremest hate,
9 526     With curses in her mouth, tears in her eyes,
9 527     The bleeding witness of my hatred by;
9 528     Having God, her conscience, and these bars against me,
9 529     And I no friends to back my suit at all
9 530     But the plain devil and dissembling looks,
9 531     And yet to win her, all the world to nothing!
9 532     Ha!
9 533     Hath she forgot already that brave prince,
9 534     Edward, her lord, whom I, some three months since,
9 535     Stabb'd in my angry mood at Tewksbury?
9 536     A sweeter and a lovelier gentleman-
9 537     Fram'd in the prodigality of nature,
9 538     Young, valiant, wise, and no doubt right royal-
9 539     The spacious world cannot again afford;
9 540     And will she yet abase her eyes on me,
9 541     That cropp'd the golden prime of this sweet prince
9 542     And made her widow to a woeful bed?
9 543     On me, whose all not equals Edward's moiety?
9 544     On me, that halts and am misshapen thus?
9 545     My dukedom to a beggarly denier,
9 546     I do mistake my person all this while.
9 547     Upon my life, she finds, although I cannot,
9 548     Myself to be a marv'llous proper man.
9 549     I'll be at charges for a looking-glass,
9 550     And entertain a score or two of tailors
9 551     To study fashions to adorn my body.
9 552     Since I am crept in favour with myself,
9 553     I will maintain it with some little cost.
9 554     But first I'll turn yon fellow in his grave,
9 555     And then return lamenting to my love.
9 556     Shine out, fair sun, till I have bought a glass,
9 557     That I may see my shadow as I pass.                     Exit
