9 598   DERBY. I do beseech you, either not believe
9 599     The envious slanders of her false accusers;
9 600     Or, if she be accus'd on true report,
9 601     Bear with her weakness, which I think proceeds
9 602     From wayward sickness and no grounded malice.
9 603   QUEEN ELIZABETH. Saw you the King to-day, my Lord of
9 604     Derby?
9 605   DERBY. But now the Duke of Buckingham and I
9 606     Are come from visiting his Majesty.
9 607   QUEEN ELIZABETH. What likelihood of his amendment,
9 608     Lords?
9 609   BUCKINGHAM. Madam, good hope; his Grace speaks
9 610     cheerfully.
9 611   QUEEN ELIZABETH. God grant him health! Did you confer
9 612     with him?
9 613   BUCKINGHAM. Ay, madam; he desires to make atonement
9 614     Between the Duke of Gloucester and your brothers,
9 615     And between them and my Lord Chamberlain;
9 616     And sent to warn them to his royal presence.
9 617   QUEEN ELIZABETH. Would all were well! But that will
9 618     never be.
9 619     I fear our happiness is at the height.
9 620 
9 621               Enter GLOUCESTER, HASTINGS, and DORSET
9 622 
9 623   GLOUCESTER. They do me wrong, and I will not endure it.
9 624     Who is it that complains unto the King
9 625     That I, forsooth, am stern and love them not?
9 626     By holy Paul, they love his Grace but lightly
9 627     That fill his ears with such dissentious rumours.
9 628     Because I cannot flatter and look fair,
9 629     Smile in men's faces, smooth, deceive, and cog,
9 630     Duck with French nods and apish courtesy,
9 631     I must be held a rancorous enemy.
9 632     Cannot a plain man live and think no harm
9 633     But thus his simple truth must be abus'd
9 634     With silken, sly, insinuating Jacks?
9 635   GREY. To who in all this presence speaks your Grace?
9 636   GLOUCESTER. To thee, that hast nor honesty nor grace.
9 637     When have I injur'd thee? when done thee wrong,
9 638     Or thee, or thee, or any of your faction?
9 639     A plague upon you all! His royal Grace-
9 640     Whom God preserve better than you would wish!-
9 641     Cannot be quiet searce a breathing while
9 642     But you must trouble him with lewd complaints.
9 643   QUEEN ELIZABETH. Brother of Gloucester, you mistake the
9 644     matter.
9 645     The King, on his own royal disposition
9 646     And not provok'd by any suitor else-
9 647     Aiming, belike, at your interior hatred
9 648     That in your outward action shows itself
9 649     Against my children, brothers, and myself-
9 650     Makes him to send that he may learn the ground.
9 651   GLOUCESTER. I cannot tell; the world is grown so bad
9 652     That wrens make prey where eagles dare not perch.
9 653     Since every Jack became a gentleman,
9 654     There's many a gentle person made a Jack.
9 655   QUEEN ELIZABETH. Come, come, we know your meaning,
9 656     brother Gloucester:
9 657     You envy my advancement and my friends';
9 658     God grant we never may have need of you!
9 659   GLOUCESTER. Meantime, God grants that I have need of you.
9 660     Our brother is imprison'd by your means,
9 661     Myself disgrac'd, and the nobility
9 662     Held in contempt; while great promotions
9 663     Are daily given to ennoble those
9 664     That scarce some two days since were worth a noble.
9 665   QUEEN ELIZABETH. By Him that rais'd me to this careful
9 666     height
9 667     From that contented hap which I enjoy'd,
9 668     I never did incense his Majesty
9 669     Against the Duke of Clarence, but have been
9 670     An earnest advocate to plead for him.
9 671     My lord, you do me shameful injury
9 672     Falsely to draw me in these vile suspects.
9 673   GLOUCESTER. You may deny that you were not the mean
9 674     Of my Lord Hastings' late imprisonment.
9 675   RIVERS. She may, my lord; for-
9 676   GLOUCESTER. She may, Lord Rivers? Why, who knows
9 677     not so?
9 678     She may do more, sir, than denying that:
9 679     She may help you to many fair preferments
9 680     And then deny her aiding hand therein,
9 681     And lay those honours on your high desert.
9 682     What may she not? She may-ay, marry, may she-
9 683   RIVERS. What, marry, may she?
9 684   GLOUCESTER. What, marry, may she? Marry with a king,
9 685     A bachelor, and a handsome stripling too.
9 686     Iwis your grandam had a worser match.
9 687   QUEEN ELIZABETH. My Lord of Gloucester, I have too long
9 688     borne
9 689     Your blunt upbraidings and your bitter scoffs.
9 690     By heaven, I will acquaint his Majesty
9 691     Of those gross taunts that oft I have endur'd.
9 692     I had rather be a country servant-maid
9 693     Than a great queen with this condition-
9 694     To be so baited, scorn'd, and stormed at.
9 695 
9 696                 Enter old QUEEN MARGARET, behind
9 697 
9 698     Small joy have I in being England's Queen.
9 699   QUEEN MARGARET. And less'ned be that small, God, I
9 700     beseech Him!
9 701     Thy honour, state, and seat, is due to me.
9 702   GLOUCESTER. What! Threat you me with telling of the
9 703     King?
9 704     Tell him and spare not. Look what I have said
9 705     I will avouch't in presence of the King.
9 706     I dare adventure to be sent to th' Tow'r.
9 707     'Tis time to speak-my pains are quite forgot.
9 708   QUEEN MARGARET. Out, devil! I do remember them to
9 709     well:
9 710     Thou kill'dst my husband Henry in the Tower,
9 711     And Edward, my poor son, at Tewksbury.
9 712   GLOUCESTER. Ere you were queen, ay, or your husband
9 713     King,
9 714     I was a pack-horse in his great affairs,
9 715     A weeder-out of his proud adversaries,
9 716     A liberal rewarder of his friends;
9 717     To royalize his blood I spent mine own.
9 718   QUEEN MARGARET. Ay, and much better blood than his or
9 719     thine.
9 720   GLOUCESTER. In all which time you and your husband Grey
9 721     Were factious for the house of Lancaster;
9 722     And, Rivers, so were you. Was not your husband
9 723     In Margaret's battle at Saint Albans slain?
9 724     Let me put in your minds, if you forget,
9 725     What you have been ere this, and what you are;
9 726     Withal, what I have been, and what I am.
9 727   QUEEN MARGARET. A murd'rous villain, and so still thou art.
9 728   GLOUCESTER. Poor Clarence did forsake his father, Warwick,
9 729     Ay, and forswore himself-which Jesu pardon!-
9 730   QUEEN MARGARET. Which God revenge!
9 731   GLOUCESTER. To fight on Edward's party for the crown;
9 732     And for his meed, poor lord, he is mewed up.
9 733     I would to God my heart were flint like Edward's,
9 734     Or Edward's soft and pitiful like mine.
9 735     I am too childish-foolish for this world.
9 736   QUEEN MARGARET. Hie thee to hell for shame and leave this
9 737     world,
9 738     Thou cacodemon; there thy kingdom is.
9 739   RIVERS. My Lord of Gloucester, in those busy days
9 740     Which here you urge to prove us enemies,
9 741     We follow'd then our lord, our sovereign king.
9 742     So should we you, if you should be our king.
9 743   GLOUCESTER. If I should be! I had rather be a pedlar.
9 744     Far be it from my heart, the thought thereof!
9 745   QUEEN ELIZABETH. As little joy, my lord, as you suppose
9 746     You should enjoy were you this country's king,
9 747     As little joy you may suppose in me
9 748     That I enjoy, being the Queen thereof.
9 749   QUEEN MARGARET. As little joy enjoys the Queen thereof;
9 750     For I am she, and altogether joyless.
9 751     I can no longer hold me patient.                 [Advancing]
9 752     Hear me, you wrangling pirates, that fall out
9 753     In sharing that which you have pill'd from me.
9 754     Which of you trembles not that looks on me?
9 755     If not that, I am Queen, you bow like subjects,
9 756     Yet that, by you depos'd, you quake like rebels?
9 757     Ah, gentle villain, do not turn away!
9 758   GLOUCESTER. Foul wrinkled witch, what mak'st thou in my
9 759     sight?
9 760   QUEEN MARGARET. But repetition of what thou hast marr'd,
9 761     That will I make before I let thee go.
9 762   GLOUCESTER. Wert thou not banished on pain of death?
9 763   QUEEN MARGARET. I was; but I do find more pain in
9 764     banishment
9 765     Than death can yield me here by my abode.
9 766     A husband and a son thou ow'st to me;
9 767     And thou a kingdom; all of you allegiance.
9 768     This sorrow that I have by right is yours;
9 769     And all the pleasures you usurp are mine.
9 770   GLOUCESTER. The curse my noble father laid on thee,
9 771     When thou didst crown his warlike brows with paper
9 772     And with thy scorns drew'st rivers from his eyes,
9 773     And then to dry them gav'st the Duke a clout
9 774     Steep'd in the faultless blood of pretty Rutland-
9 775     His curses then from bitterness of soul
9 776     Denounc'd against thee are all fall'n upon thee;
9 777     And God, not we, hath plagu'd thy bloody deed.
9 778   QUEEN ELIZABETH. So just is God to right the innocent.
9 779   HASTINGS. O, 'twas the foulest deed to slay that babe,
9 780     And the most merciless that e'er was heard of!
9 781   RIVERS. Tyrants themselves wept when it was reported.
9 782   DORSET. No man but prophesied revenge for it.
9 783   BUCKINGHAM. Northumberland, then present, wept to see it.
9 784   QUEEN MARGARET. What, were you snarling all before I came,
9 785     Ready to catch each other by the throat,
9 786     And turn you all your hatred now on me?
9 787     Did York's dread curse prevail so much with heaven
9 788     That Henry's death, my lovely Edward's death,
9 789     Their kingdom's loss, my woeful banishment,
9 790     Should all but answer for that peevish brat?
9 791     Can curses pierce the clouds and enter heaven?
9 792     Why then, give way, dull clouds, to my quick curses!
9 793     Though not by war, by surfeit die your king,
9 794     As ours by murder, to make him a king!
9 795     Edward thy son, that now is Prince of Wales,
9 796     For Edward our son, that was Prince of Wales,
9 797     Die in his youth by like untimely violence!
9 798     Thyself a queen, for me that was a queen,
9 799     Outlive thy glory, like my wretched self!
9 800     Long mayest thou live to wail thy children's death,
9 801     And see another, as I see thee now,
9 802     Deck'd in thy rights, as thou art stall'd in mine!
9 803     Long die thy happy days before thy death;
9 804     And, after many length'ned hours of grief,
9 805     Die neither mother, wife, nor England's Queen!
9 806     Rivers and Dorset, you were standers by,
9 807     And so wast thou, Lord Hastings, when my son
9 808     Was stabb'd with bloody daggers. God, I pray him,
9 809     That none of you may live his natural age,
9 810     But by some unlook'd accident cut off!
9 811   GLOUCESTER. Have done thy charm, thou hateful wither'd
9 812     hag.
9 813   QUEEN MARGARET. And leave out thee? Stay, dog, for thou
9 814     shalt hear me.
9 815     If heaven have any grievous plague in store
9 816     Exceeding those that I can wish upon thee,
9 817     O, let them keep it till thy sins be ripe,
9 818     And then hurl down their indignation
9 819     On thee, the troubler of the poor world's peace!
9 820     The worm of conscience still be-gnaw thy soul!
9 821     Thy friends suspect for traitors while thou liv'st,
9 822     And take deep traitors for thy dearest friends!
9 823     No sleep close up that deadly eye of thine,
9 824     Unless it be while some tormenting dream
9 825     Affrights thee with a hell of ugly devils!
9 826     Thou elvish-mark'd, abortive, rooting hog,
9 827     Thou that wast seal'd in thy nativity
9 828     The slave of nature and the son of hell,
9 829     Thou slander of thy heavy mother's womb,
9 830     Thou loathed issue of thy father's loins,
9 831     Thou rag of honour, thou detested-
9 832   GLOUCESTER. Margaret!
9 833   QUEEN MARGARET. Richard!
9 834   GLOUCESTER. Ha?
9 835   QUEEN MARGARET. I call thee not.
9 836   GLOUCESTER. I cry thee mercy then, for I did think
9 837     That thou hadst call'd me all these bitter names.
9 838   QUEEN MARGARET. Why, so I did, but look'd for no reply.
9 839     O, let me make the period to my curse!
9 840   GLOUCESTER. 'Tis done by me, and ends in-Margaret.
9 841   QUEEN ELIZABETH. Thus have you breath'd your curse
9 842     against yourself.
9 843   QUEEN MARGARET. Poor painted queen, vain flourish of my
9 844     fortune!
9 845     Why strew'st thou sugar on that bottled spider
9 846     Whose deadly web ensnareth thee about?
9 847     Fool, fool! thou whet'st a knife to kill thyself.
9 848     The day will come that thou shalt wish for me
9 849     To help thee curse this poisonous bunch-back'd toad.
9 850   HASTINGS. False-boding woman, end thy frantic curse,
9 851     Lest to thy harm thou move our patience.
9 852   QUEEN MARGARET. Foul shame upon you! you have all
9 853     mov'd mine.
9 854   RIVERS. Were you well serv'd, you would be taught your
9 855       duty.
9 856   QUEEN MARGARET. To serve me well you all should do me
9 857     duty,
9 858     Teach me to be your queen and you my subjects.
9 859     O, serve me well, and teach yourselves that duty!
9 860   DORSET. Dispute not with her; she is lunatic.
9 861   QUEEN MARGARET. Peace, Master Marquis, you are malapert;
9 862     Your fire-new stamp of honour is scarce current.
9 863     O, that your young nobility could judge
9 864     What 'twere to lose it and be miserable!
9 865     They that stand high have many blasts to shake them,
9 866     And if they fall they dash themselves to pieces.
9 867   GLOUCESTER. Good counsel, marry; learn it, learn it, Marquis.
9 868   DORSET. It touches you, my lord, as much as me.
9 869   GLOUCESTER. Ay, and much more; but I was born so high,
9 870     Our aery buildeth in the cedar's top,
9 871     And dallies with the wind, and scorns the sun.
9 872   QUEEN MARGARET. And turns the sun to shade-alas! alas!
9 873     Witness my son, now in the shade of death,
9 874     Whose bright out-shining beams thy cloudy wrath
9 875     Hath in eternal darkness folded up.
9 876     Your aery buildeth in our aery's nest.
9 877     O God that seest it, do not suffer it;
9 878     As it is won with blood, lost be it so!
9 879   BUCKINGHAM. Peace, peace, for shame, if not for charity!
9 880   QUEEN MARGARET. Urge neither charity nor shame to me.
9 881     Uncharitably with me have you dealt,
9 882     And shamefully my hopes by you are butcher'd.
9 883     My charity is outrage, life my shame;
9 884     And in that shame still live my sorrow's rage!
9 885   BUCKINGHAM. Have done, have done.
9 886   QUEEN MARGARET. O princely Buckingham, I'll kiss thy
9 887     hand
9 888     In sign of league and amity with thee.
9 889     Now fair befall thee and thy noble house!
9 890     Thy garments are not spotted with our blood,
9 891     Nor thou within the compass of my curse.
9 892   BUCKINGHAM. Nor no one here; for curses never pass
9 893     The lips of those that breathe them in the air.
9 894   QUEEN MARGARET. I will not think but they ascend the sky
9 895     And there awake God's gentle-sleeping peace.
9 896     O Buckingham, take heed of yonder dog!
9 897     Look when he fawns, he bites; and when he bites,
9 898     His venom tooth will rankle to the death:
9 899     Have not to do with him, beware of him;
9 900     Sin, death, and hell, have set their marks on him,
9 901     And all their ministers attend on him.
9 902   GLOUCESTER. What doth she say, my Lord of Buckingham?
9 903   BUCKINGHAM. Nothing that I respect, my gracious lord.
9 904   QUEEN MARGARET. What, dost thou scorn me for my gentle
9 905     counsel,
9 906     And soothe the devil that I warn thee from?
9 907     O, but remember this another day,
9 908     When he shall split thy very heart with sorrow,
9 909     And say poor Margaret was a prophetess!
9 910     Live each of you the subjects to his hate,
9 911     And he to yours, and all of you to God's!               Exit
9 912   BUCKINGHAM. My hair doth stand an end to hear her curses.
9 913   RIVERS. And so doth mine. I muse why she's at liberty.
9 914   GLOUCESTER. I cannot blame her; by God's holy Mother,
9 915     She hath had too much wrong; and I repent
9 916     My part thereof that I have done to her.
9 917   QUEEN ELIZABETH. I never did her any to my knowledge.
9 918   GLOUCESTER. Yet you have all the vantage of her wrong.
9 919     I was too hot to do somebody good
9 920     That is too cold in thinking of it now.
9 921     Marry, as for Clarence, he is well repaid;
9 922     He is frank'd up to fatting for his pains;
9 923     God pardon them that are the cause thereof!
9 924   RIVERS. A virtuous and a Christian-like conclusion,
9 925     To pray for them that have done scathe to us!
9 926   GLOUCESTER. So do I ever-  [Aside]  being well advis'd;
9 927     For had I curs'd now, I had curs'd myself.
9 928 
9 929                          Enter CATESBY
9 930 
9 931   CATESBY. Madam, his Majesty doth can for you,
9 932     And for your Grace, and you, my gracious lords.
9 933   QUEEN ELIZABETH. Catesby, I come. Lords, will you go
9 934     with me?
9 935   RIVERS. We wait upon your Grace.
9 936                                        Exeunt all but GLOUCESTER
9 937   GLOUCESTER. I do the wrong, and first begin to brawl.
9 938     The secret mischiefs that I set abroach
9 939     I lay unto the grievous charge of others.
9 940     Clarence, who I indeed have cast in darkness,
9 941     I do beweep to many simple gulls;
9 942     Namely, to Derby, Hastings, Buckingham;
9 943     And tell them 'tis the Queen and her allies
9 944     That stir the King against the Duke my brother.
9 945     Now they believe it, and withal whet me
9 946     To be reveng'd on Rivers, Dorset, Grey;
9 947     But then I sigh and, with a piece of Scripture,
9 948     Tell them that God bids us do good for evil.
9 949     And thus I clothe my naked villainy
9 950     With odd old ends stol'n forth of holy writ,
9 951     And seem a saint when most I play the devil.
9 952 
9 953                        Enter two MURDERERS
9 954 
9 955     But, soft, here come my executioners.
9 956     How now, my hardy stout resolved mates!
9 957     Are you now going to dispatch this thing?
9 958   FIRST MURDERER. We are, my lord, and come to have the
9 959     warrant,
9 960     That we may be admitted where he is.
9 961   GLOUCESTER. Well thought upon; I have it here about me.
9 962                                              [Gives the warrant]
9 963     When you have done, repair to Crosby Place.
9 964     But, sirs, be sudden in the execution,
9 965     Withal obdurate, do not hear him plead;
9 966     For Clarence is well-spoken, and perhaps
9 967     May move your hearts to pity, if you mark him.
9 968   FIRST MURDERER. Tut, tut, my lord, we will not stand to
9 969     prate;
9 970     Talkers are no good doers. Be assur'd
9 971     We go to use our hands and not our tongues.
9 972   GLOUCESTER. Your eyes drop millstones when fools' eyes fall
9 973     tears.
9 974     I like you, lads; about your business straight;
9 975     Go, go, dispatch.
9 976   FIRST MURDERER. We will, my noble lord.                 Exeunt
