9 981 SCENE 4.
9 982 
9 983 London. The Tower
9 984 
9 985 Enter CLARENCE and KEEPER
9 986 
9 987   KEEPER. Why looks your Grace so heavily to-day?
9 988   CLARENCE. O, I have pass'd a miserable night,
9 989     So full of fearful dreams, of ugly sights,
9 990     That, as I am a Christian faithful man,
9 991     I would not spend another such a night
9 992     Though 'twere to buy a world of happy days-
9 993     So full of dismal terror was the time!
9 994   KEEPER. What was your dream, my lord? I pray you
9 995     tell me.
9 996   CLARENCE. Methoughts that I had broken from the Tower
9 997     And was embark'd to cross to Burgundy;
9 998     And in my company my brother Gloucester,
9 999     Who from my cabin tempted me to walk
9 1000     Upon the hatches. Thence we look'd toward England,
9 1001     And cited up a thousand heavy times,
9 1002     During the wars of York and Lancaster,
9 1003     That had befall'n us. As we pac'd along
9 1004     Upon the giddy footing of the hatches,
9 1005     Methought that Gloucester stumbled, and in falling
9 1006     Struck me, that thought to stay him, overboard
9 1007     Into the tumbling billows of the main.
9 1008     O Lord, methought what pain it was to drown,
9 1009     What dreadful noise of waters in my ears,
9 1010     What sights of ugly death within my eyes!
9 1011     Methoughts I saw a thousand fearful wrecks,
9 1012     A thousand men that fishes gnaw'd upon,
9 1013     Wedges of gold, great anchors, heaps of pearl,
9 1014     Inestimable stones, unvalued jewels,
9 1015     All scatt'red in the bottom of the sea;
9 1016     Some lay in dead men's skulls, and in the holes
9 1017     Where eyes did once inhabit there were crept,
9 1018     As 'twere in scorn of eyes, reflecting gems,
