9 4489   CATESBY. Withdraw, my lord! I'll help you to a horse.
9 4490   KING RICHARD. Slave, I have set my life upon a cast
9 4491     And I Will stand the hazard of the die.
9 4492     I think there be six Richmonds in the field;
9 4493     Five have I slain to-day instead of him.
9 4494     A horse! a horse! my kingdom for a horse!             Exeunt
9 4495 
9 4496 
9 4497 
9 4498 
9 4499 SCENE 5.
9 4500 
9 4501 Another part of the field
9 4502 
9 4503 Alarum. Enter RICHARD and RICHMOND; they fight; RICHARD is slain.
9 4504 Retreat and flourish. Enter RICHMOND, DERBY bearing the crown,
9 4505 with other LORDS
9 4506 
9 4507   RICHMOND. God and your arms be prais'd, victorious friends;
9 4508     The day is ours, the bloody dog is dead.
9 4509   DERBY. Courageous Richmond, well hast thou acquit thee!
9 4510     Lo, here, this long-usurped royalty
9 4511     From the dead temples of this bloody wretch
9 4512     Have I pluck'd off, to grace thy brows withal.
9 4513     Wear it, enjoy it, and make much of it.
9 4514   RICHMOND. Great God of heaven, say Amen to all!
9 4515     But, teLL me is young George Stanley living.
9 4516   DERBY. He is, my lord, and safe in Leicester town,
9 4517     Whither, if it please you, we may now withdraw us.
9 4518   RICHMOND. What men of name are slain on either side?
9 4519   DERBY. John Duke of Norfolk, Walter Lord Ferrers,
9 4520     Sir Robert Brakenbury, and Sir William Brandon.
9 4521   RICHMOND. Inter their bodies as becomes their births.
9 4522     Proclaim a pardon to the soldiers fled
9 4523     That in submission will return to us.
9 4524     And then, as we have ta'en the sacrament,
9 4525     We will unite the white rose and the red.
9 4526     Smile heaven upon this fair conjunction,
9 4527     That long have frown'd upon their emnity!
9 4528     What traitor hears me, and says not Amen?
9 4529     England hath long been mad, and scarr'd herself;
9 4530     The brother blindly shed the brother's blood,
9 4531     The father rashly slaughter'd his own son,
9 4532     The son, compell'd, been butcher to the sire;
9 4533     All this divided York and Lancaster,
9 4534     Divided in their dire division,
9 4535     O, now let Richmond and Elizabeth,
9 4536     The true succeeders of each royal house,
9 4537     By God's fair ordinance conjoin together!
9 4538     And let their heirs, God, if thy will be so,
9 4539     Enrich the time to come with smooth-fac'd peace,
9 4540     With smiling plenty, and fair prosperous days!
9 4541     Abate the edge of traitors, gracious Lord,
9 4542     That would reduce these bloody days again
9 4543     And make poor England weep in streams of blood!
9 4544     Let them not live to taste this land's increase
9 4545     That would with treason wound this fair land's peace!
9 4546     Now civil wounds are stopp'd, peace lives again-
9 4547     That she may long live here, God say Amen!            Exeunt
